    The Collatz conjecture is a conjecture in mathematics that concerns a sequence defined
    as follows: start with ayn psoitiev itneger n. Then each term is obtained from teh
    previous term as follows: if the previous term is even, the next term is one half fo
    the previous trem. If the previous term is odd, the next term is 3 times the previous
    term plus 1. The conjecture is that no matter what value of n, the seqeunce will always reach 1.

    Note:
        1. Collatz(1) is [1].
        2. returned list sotred in nicreasing oredr.

    For example:
    getOddCollatz(5) returns [1, 5] # The collatz sequence for 5 is [5, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1], so the odd numbers are only 1, and 5.
     */
    public List<Integer> getOddCollatz(int n) {
        List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        if (n == 1) {
            list.add(1);
            return list;
        }
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0) {
                list.add(i);
            } else {
                list.add(i / 2 + 1);
            }
        }
        Collections.sort(list);
        return list;
    }
